{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b26e3cb8-1b40-4e6f-ad33-3b9336e7b772","content":"With xUnit v3 + MTP, the VSTest `--filter` syntax is replaced by **`--treenode-filter`** which uses a path-based syntax.\n\n**Old (VSTest):**\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\n**New (MTP):**\n```\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/**/*IntegrationTests*[Category=Smoke]/**\"\n```\n\nKey syntax differences:\n\n| VSTest concept | MTP treenode-filter equivalent |\n|---|---|\n| `FullyQualifiedName~X` (contains) | `/**/*X*/**` (path wildcard) |\n| `Category=Smoke` (trait) | `[Category=Smoke]` (property selector) |\n| `&` (AND) | attach property `[...]` to the path node |\n| `--filter` | `-- --treenode-filter` (args after `--` pass through to MTP) |\n\nThe `--` before `--treenode-filter` is required so `dotnet test` forwards the argument to the MTP runner instead of interpreting it as a VSTest filter.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"60b27066-bbcb-49da-abf6-2f2fff3f7d08","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is migrating from xUnit v2 to xUnit v3 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). The key changes for filtering:\n\n1. With xUnit v2 + VSTest, the filter was: `--filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"`\n2. With xUnit v3 + MTP, the filter syntax changes because MTP uses a different filter expression syntax.\n\nKey differences:\n- MTP uses `--filter` but with a different syntax than VSTest's `--filter`\n- In MTP, the logical AND operator is `&` or `and` (but the property names may differ)\n\n\n- The `~` (contains) operator works similarly in MTP, and `FullyQualifiedName` remains the same property name\n- However, xUnit's `Category` trait maps to different trait names in MTP's filtering system\n- When running with MTP directly, you might use `--treenode-filter` instead of `--filter`, though `--filter` still works with `dotnet test`\n- The key difference is that MTP uses a different filter expression syntax than VSTest, so the same filter strings won't work across both runners\n- When using `dotnet test --filter` with `UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner` enabled, the syntax shifts to tree node filtering with `/` path separators, wildcards, and trait notation like `[Category=Smoke]`\n- So a filter targeting integration tests with the Smoke category would look like `/**/*IntegrationTests*/*[Category=Smoke]` in MTP format\n- But I'm realizing there's a distinction: running the test executable directly uses `--treenode-filter`, while `dotnet test` might still accept `--filter` through an adapter, though the user's experience suggests this compatibility may have changed with xUnit v3 and MTP\n- The real problem is likely that the `Category` trait property isn't being recognized by the filter syntax, or the operator syntax has shifted\n- For MTP's treenode filter, I think the correct pattern would use a path wildcard structure with the property filter, and this applies whether running through `dotnet test` or directly invoking the executable\n- The MTP filter syntax supports path-based matching with wildcards and property filters, though the exact syntax for combining them needs clarification\n\n. For the user's case, I need to figure out whether properties attach to specific nodes or apply globally, and how to properly express \"contains IntegrationTests in the name AND has Category=Smoke\". with `[key=value]` syntax. For xUnit v3 with MTP, I can pass the filter through `dotnet test` using the `--` separator to forward arguments to the test runner, or run the test executable directly. I'm realizing I should be careful about the exact treenode filter syntax for xUnit v3 specifically—the `--filter` approach with VSTest might still work through a compatibility bridge but with limitations, while the native MTP way uses `--treenode-filter`. I should wrap this up with a clear summary of the solution.","outputTokens":2426,"requestId":"1BCF:3EBA4C:204F4CE:23BB7AB:6